Note: Datasets are up to 04/26/22

Covid Introduction¶

Covid-19 is a respitory illness caused by SARS-CoV-2, a coroanvirus that was first discovered in Wuhan China in Decomber of 2019. The coronavirus spreads through air droplets that are released when a person coughs, sneezes, talks, or simply breathes. Symptoms include cough, fever, chills, aches, headache, fatigue, congestions, and loss of taste and smell. Though symptoms are usually mild, severe illnesss resulting in hospitalization is possible, especially for older individuals or people with underlying conditions. The spread of Covid-19 caused a panedmic in the United States (and the world). In the United States, most Covid-19 policies and procedures were instituted at a state level. Additionally, people's background (age, ethnicity, religion, political affiliation, etc.) played a large role in how cautious they were with avoiding the disease. In this work, we examine the per-capita covid cases in each state and examine which demographic factors have explanatory power of these trends. This will hopefully explain the demographic factors that caused both personal decisions on how to respond to the pandemic as well as policy decisions in certain states. The knowledge of these demographic trends could influence future policy decisions related to public healh policy. Apart from demographics we also want to answer the question of how well the US did compare to the rest of the world. This can give us insight on how well our policies and lockdowns helped suppress the spread of COVID-19.

An important thing to note is that we'll only look at the 50 states in the US and so we'll be ignoring other US owned territories such as Puerto Rico, Guam, Northern Mariana Islands, the U.S. Virgin Islands, and American Samoa.

The John's Hopkins curated dataset can be found here. For our analysis, we'll be using the time series csv file for confirmed cases and deaths within the United States. Each dataset has a list of counties in the United States along with its corresponding state, and lists the confirmed covid cases on each day since the start of the pandemic (1/22/2020 for our purposes) up to April 25, 2022. The data comes from Johns Hopkins University's Covid-19 Data repository, one of the most well-respected sources for Covid-19 data in the world (and one of the most well-respected Universities in the world).

We see that the only missing values are related to the FIPS code. However, we would not need the FIPS code as once we group each one of these counties by state, we won't be needing these codes. Therefore, we can safely ignore these missing values.

An observation to note is that the dataset above has each date as an individual column thus making the table too "wide". This in turn makes it harder in analyzing the date (albeit it's easier to read). We'll convert the table from the current wide format to a long format by turning each date column into their own row through a process called melting. More information about melting can be found here.

Now we have the total number of cases fo each state for each date. However, another metric we want is the number of daily cases each day which is defined by the total cases today minus the total cases yesterday.

We'll manipulate our dataframe so that we have an additional column called daily_cases defined as above. We'll take advatange of pandas's diff() function which allows us to compute the difference of a column between consecutive rows in one line. One issue with directly doing this is that at positions where we transition from one state to the next, we can have large negative values because diff() is subtracting the most recent total cases for one state from the oldest total cases for a different state. To circumvent this, we'll filter and perform the diff() separetly for each state.

In [40]:
# getting a list of states in our dataset
states = np.unique(confirmed_US['Province_State'].values)
totalCases_US['daily_cases'] = np.NaN # instanstiating with default value of NaN

# iterating through each state
for s in states:
    filtered = totalCases_US.loc[totalCases_US['Province_State'] == s] # getting a separate  dataframe for each state
    totalCases_US.loc[totalCases_US['Province_State'] == s, 'daily_cases']= filtered['Cases'].diff() # adding daily_cases

totalCases_US[(totalCases_US['Province_State'] == "Maryland") & (totalCases_US['Cases'] > 0)].head(10)

Exploratory data analysis¶

General Trend of Covid Cases¶

In this next step, we want to get a feel for the data through visualizing and computing summary statistics for our dataset. Through the plots and statisitcs, we'll be able to notice trends in the data as well as the distribution. These key insights will give us an idea of what approaches we should take for our machine learning algorithms.

To a general idea of trend, we'll first plot a graphic of the number of daily cases for the entire US.

In [46]:
# Adding up all the daily cases from all states per date
totalDailyCasesUS = totalCases_US.groupby(['Date']).agg({'daily_cases': 'sum'})
totalDailyCasesUS.reset_index(inplace=True) # reseting index so that date isn't the index

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5)) 
ax.plot(totalDailyCasesUS['Date'], totalDailyCasesUS['daily_cases']) #line plot 
plt.xlabel("Date");
plt.ylabel("Daily Cases");
fig.suptitle("Daily Cases in the US");

We can see that during periods such as 2020-10 to 2021-03 there was a large spike in daily cases. And an even larger spike came across in 2022-01. Due to this spike however, our $y$-ranges are too large to be able to notice smaller trends. In order to amend this we'll take the log of the cases.

In [47]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5)) 
totalDailyCasesUS['log'] = np.log10(totalDailyCasesUS['daily_cases'].replace(0, np.NaN))
np.log10(totalDailyCasesUS['daily_cases'].replace(0, np.nan))
ax.plot(totalDailyCasesUS['Date'], totalDailyCasesUS['log'])
plt.xlabel("Date");
plt.ylabel("Daily Cases");
fig.suptitle("Daily Cases in the US");

Now we can notice the trend smaller daily cases values more clearly. A thing to note from this graph is that we can see a sharp increase near the start of the pandemic which is not observed anywhere else. Additionally the massive spikes in cases at the start of 2022 is nowhere as extreme as it was in the non-log graph.

Demographics¶

A main relationship we would like to examine is whether the demographics of a state has an association with COVID cases. Certain demographic factors may have a relationship with Covid-19 cases per capita because these demographic factors could relate to how cautious individuals are of the disease, their ability to alter their lives to avoid infection, and the policies their state government put in place to reduce the spread of the disease. As an example of this line of thinking, consider the demographic of age. States with a large number of older individuals may have less Covid-19 cases per capita since these older individuals are more susceptible to severe outcomes from the disease and would thus try harder to avoid infection. State government policies could also reflect this by instituting stricter precautions and lockdown measures.

Since there's numerous demographic columns in our states_demographic dataframe, we'll define a function that plots the variables that we want to show a relationship between.

In [48]:
# getting on the total cases accumulated by 04-25-22
end_date = datetime.datetime.strptime("2022-04-25", '%Y-%m-%d')
datefilter = totalCases_US.loc[totalCases_US['Date'] == end_date].copy()

However, before we plot the various demographic factors we want our dependent variable (cases) to be relatively small in range. An issue with just plotting demographic factor by total case is that intuitively states with larger populations will have more cases. And so to avoid having the range of the graph skewed by this, we'll make our dependent variable cases per capita instead. This way our $y$-range is $\in [0,1]$ and we can better assses visually whether there is a significant association with an individual factor.

In [110]:
#datefilter= datefilter.drop(9074)
state_demographics = state_demographics.drop(2)

datefilter['cases_per_capita'] = np.NaN
for i, row in datefilter.iterrows():
    s = row["Province_State"]
    population = state_demographics[state_demographics['State'] == s]['Population.2020 Population']
    datefilter.at[i, 'cases_per_capita'] = (row["Cases"]/float(population))

def plot_by(demographic, x_title, title, run_regression):
    states = np.unique(state_demographics['State'])
    datefilter[demographic] = np.NaN
    
    for i, row in datefilter.iterrows():
        s = row["Province_State"]
        population = state_demographics[state_demographics['State'] == s]['Population.2020 Population'].values
        if (len(population) >= 1) :
            demo = state_demographics[state_demographics['State'] == s][demographic].values[0]
            datefilter.at[i, demographic]= demo
            
    # Picking colors from a colorwheel for each scatter point
    phi = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, len(states))
    x = np.sin(phi)
    y = np.cos(phi)
    rgb_cycle = np.vstack((            
            .5*(1.+np.cos(phi)), 
            .5*(1.+np.cos(phi+2*np.pi/3)), 
            .5*(1.+np.cos(phi-2*np.pi/3)))).T 
    
    x = datefilter[demographic].values.reshape(-1, 1)
    # y = list(datefilter['Cases'].values)
    #y = np.array(cases_per_capita)
    y = np.array(datefilter['cases_per_capita'])
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,8))
    #sns.scatterplot(x=x,y=y,palette="Set2")
    
    if run_regression: 
        linear_regressor = LinearRegression()  # create object for the class
        linear_regressor.fit(x, y)  # perform linear regression
        Y_pred = linear_regressor.predict(x)
        plt.plot(x, Y_pred, color='red')
    
    
    plt.scatter(x, y, c=rgb_cycle, s=90)
    
    
    # Adding teamID to each scatter point
    for i, txt in enumerate(states):
        plt.annotate(us_state_to_abbrev[txt], (x[i], y[i]))
        
    plt.ylabel("Covid-19 Cases Per Capita")
    plt.xlabel(x_title)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()
    return x,y

US vs World¶

One thing that we want to know is how the US's cases_per_capita compares to the rest of the world. We want to know how better or worse do we fare in terms of percent cases against the rest of the world. This can give us insight on how well overall we handled COVID in terms of protocols, state-wide safety measures, and personal responsibility. In order to perform this we have to import some more datasets in which we'll perform the same set of operations on as prior.

Below we'll be importing the global cases from the same Johns Hopkins dataset as well as 2020 Global population data obtained from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/tanuprabhu/population-by-country-2020

There at 15 missing values for cases_per_capita in our dataframe. However, some of these entries are not from a country (i.e Olympics, Diamond Princess). We'll drop the ones that aren't a country and for the others, we'll replace the missing values with the average of the 10 closest countries to the same number of cases. For instance with Antarctica, we'll find the 10 countires that are closest to 11 cases and use the average of those 10 as a replacement. Below is the code to do that.

Now that we have finished cleaning up our dataset we can get into the hypothesis testing.

We'll use a 2-sample hypothesis test here to test the difference in means. In order to do this we'll first have to determine an appropriate test-statistic as what our null $H_0$ and alternate $H_a$ hypotheses are.

An appropriate choice of a null hypothesis here would be to assume that there is no different between the mean cases per capita of the US and the rest of the world. This can be written as: $$H_0: \mu_{US} = \mu_{World} $$ To figure out an appropriate alternate hypothesis lets take a look at our data, especially what both of our means are.

In [100]:
meanUS = np.mean(datefilter['cases_per_capita']) # mean cases_per_capita for the US
meanUS
Out[100]:
0.24775579468154468
In [101]:
meanGlobal = np.mean(datefilter_Global['cases_per_capita']) # mean_cases_per_capita for the rest of the world
meanGlobal
Out[101]:
0.1287842781846342

Here we can see that the US has a noticably higher cases per capita. Therefore, our data already suggests that our alternate hypothesis should be that: $$H_a: \mu_{US} > \mu_{Global} $$ Thus, if we reject our null hypothesis, we have significant evidence to claim that the US has a higher cases per capita.

As for the test statistic, we use either a $z$ test statistic or a $t$ test statistic depending on what assumptions we can make on our data. An important assumption to check for is normality. This assumption can be checked using a normal probabiltiy plot, which we will do below.

In [102]:
import numpy as np
import statsmodels.api as sm
import scipy.stats as stats
import pylab as py

stats.probplot(datefilter['cases_per_capita'], dist="norm", plot=py)
py.show()

We see from the normal probability plot that the points fall near the straight line and do show a linear trend. Therefore it is reasonable to assume normality for the US.

In [103]:
stats.probplot(datefilter_Global['cases_per_capita'], dist="norm", plot=py)
py.show()

We see that the normal probability plot for the global cases per capita does not follow a straight line, and so we cannot assume normality for the rest of the world. Thus, we can not use a $t$-statistic here as we do not have evidence to support the assumption of normality. However, since both data sizes are large $>40$ we can employ the large sample $z$-test instead where our test-statistic is: $$Z = \dfrac{\overline{x}_{US} - \overline{x}_{Global}}{\sqrt{\dfrac{s_{US}^2}{n} + \dfrac{s_{Global}^2}{m}}}$$

To obtain our test result we then have to calculate our $p$-value. A $p$-value is defined as the probability (under the assumption that the null hypothesis is true) of finding evidence that is equal to or worse than the test statistic calculated from the given data. Since we're using a $z$-statistic, we'll use the normal cumulative probability density function ($\Phi(z)$) to calculate our p-value. Since our alternate hypothesis is $\geq$ we're performing an upper-tailed test and so our p-value can be expressed as : $$p=1-\Phi(Z)$$ We'll also use the standard significance level $\alpha$ of 0.05. This means that if our calculated $p$-value is less than our $\alpha$ we have significant evidence to reject $H_0$

Below we'll calculate our test-statistic and our p-value.

In [104]:
from scipy.stats import norm # importing normal cdf cuntion

def p_value(us, globe):
    sdUS = np.std(us['cases_per_capita']) # US standard deviation
    sdGlobal = np.std(globe['cases_per_capita']) # Global standard deviation
    n = len(us['cases_per_capita']) # US data size
    m = len(globe['cases_per_capita']) # global data size
    z = (meanUS - meanGlobal)/( (sdUS/np.sqrt(n)) + (sdGlobal/np.sqrt(m)) ) # z-statistic

    p = 1-norm.cdf(z) # calculating our p-value
    return p

p_value(datefilter, datefilter_Global)
Out[104]:
1.3211653993039363e-14

We see that our $p$-value $\approx 0 < \alpha = 0.05$. Since our p-value is so small, we can conclusively reject our null hypothesis and accept our alternate that the mean cases per capita of the US is larger than the mean cases per capita of the rest of the world.

One thing to note is that we have to remember we're using cases per capita. This means that countries with higher populations are weighted the same as countries with lower populations. We have 197 countries which means we can have numerous countries with very low case rates which will skew the data towards the lower side even if larger countries such as China, Russia, UK, Canada, etc have a high case rate. Therefore, one thing we can do is to take the $m \geq 40$ highest population countries and calculate the $p$-value using only those. To see how this method affects our p-value we'll calculate numerous $p$-values with different $m$'s and see whether or not we still reject $H_0$.

In [108]:
num_max = [i for i in range(40, len(datefilter_Global['cases_per_capita']), 5)] # our different m's (>= 40)
p_values = [] # storing a list of p-values for later plot

# iterating through each m value and adding the calculate p-value
for x in num_max:
    countries_list = population_Global.sort_values(by=['Population (2020)'], ascending=False).head(x)['Country (or dependency)']
    p_values.append(p_value(datefilter, datefilter_Global[datefilter_Global['Country/Region'].isin(countries_list)]))
    
# plotting our p-value vs m
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.xlabel('Number of Largest Countries (m)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('P-value', fontsize=12)
plt.plot(num_max, p_values, '-ok');

Here we see that even at all values of $m$ we still conclusively reject the null hypothesis. This shows that even comparing against the $m$ largest countries in the world to reduce the effects of smaller population countries, the hypothesis test still suggets that the US has a larger mean cases per capita. However despite knowing this information we still can't suggest a reason for why this is the case. Note that our cases per capita was calculated using the culumative case counts by 04/25/22. Which means that all the factors such as handling of the initial outbreak, policies enacted during the outbreak, lockdown procedures, etc. are all factored into this case per capita calculation. Thus the only conclusion we can make from our hypothesis test conclusion that the US did worse overall than the rest of the world.
